#let images = (
  "15-1": (
    caption: [Stages involved in the migration of white blood cells from blood vessels into tissues. The figure depicts a neutrophil (嗜中性粒细胞) that goes through the stages of rolling, capture, adhesion and activation, and finally extravasation (diapedesis, 渗出/穿越) through the blood vessel wall. This process is triggered when invading bacteria secrete certain chemicals that attract and activate white blood cells, requiring specific molecular binding between the white blood cell surface and endothelial cell receptors.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "15-2": (
    caption: [Phagocytosis (吞噬作用) by a neutrophil or macrophage (巨噬细胞). A phagocytic cell extends its pseudopods (伪足) around the object to be engulfed (such as a bacterium). If the pseudopods fuse to form a complete food vacuole, lysosomal enzymes (溶酶体酶) are restricted to the organelle formed by the lysosome and food vacuole. If the lysosome fuses with the vacuole before fusion of the pseudopods is complete, lysosomal enzymes are released into the infected area of tissue.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "15-3": (
    caption: [Life cycle of the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV, 人类免疫缺陷病毒). The virus binds to the CD4 receptor (CD4受体) on the host cell surface, enters the cell, and uses reverse transcriptase (逆转录酶) to synthesize DNA from its RNA genome. This viral DNA is integrated into the host cell's DNA and directs the synthesis of new viral particles that are assembled and released from the cell.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "15-4": (
    caption: [An immunoassay (免疫测定) using the agglutination (凝集) technique. Red blood cells can be used to demonstrate this technique because the antibodies (抗体) can bind to antigens (抗原) on the red blood cell surface, causing the cells to clump together (agglutinate). This is the basis for blood typing tests.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "15-5": (
    caption: [The events in a local inflammation (局部炎症). Antigens on the surface of bacterial cells bind to antibodies, which coat the bacteria. This activates complement (补体) and promotes phagocytosis by neutrophils and macrophages. Histamine (组胺) released from mast cells (肥大细胞) causes vasodilation (血管舒张) and increased capillary permeability (毛细血管通透性), leading to the characteristic signs of inflammation: redness, heat, swelling, and pain.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "15-6": (
    caption: [Infiltration of an inflamed site by leukocytes (白细胞). Different types of leukocytes infiltrate the site of a local inflammation over time. Neutrophils (嗜中性粒细胞) arrive first within hours, followed by monocytes (单核细胞) which peak around 24-48 hours, and then lymphocytes (淋巴细胞) which arrive later and may persist for days, demonstrating the temporal sequence of immune cell recruitment during the inflammatory response.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "15-7": (
    caption: [B lymphocytes (B淋巴细胞) are stimulated to become plasma cells (浆细胞) and memory cells (记忆细胞). B lymphocytes have antibodies on their surface that function as receptors for specific antigens. The interaction of antigens and antibodies on the surface stimulates cell division and the maturation of the B cell progeny into memory cells and plasma cells. Plasma cells produce and secrete large amounts of antibody, as evidenced by their extensive rough endoplasmic reticulum (粗面内质网).],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "15-8": (
    caption: [Antibodies bind to antigens on bacteria. A pathogen such as a bacterial cell has many antigens on its surface, which can activate B cells that produce antibodies against those antigens. Each antibody is composed of four polypeptide chains (多肽链)—two are heavy (H) chains, and two are light (L) chains. Regions that have constant amino acid sequences are abbreviated C, and those with variable amino acid sequences are abbreviated V. Antigens bind to the variable regions. Each antibody is divided into antigen-binding fragments (Fab, 抗原结合片段) and a crystallizable fragment (Fc, 可结晶片段).],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "15-9": (
    caption: [The antigen-binding site of an antibody. The structure of the Fab portion of an antibody molecule and the antigen with which it combines as determined by X-ray diffraction (X射线衍射). The heavy and light chains of the antibody are shown, demonstrating the complementary shape (互补形状) at the region where antigen and antibody join together, illustrating the specificity of antibody-antigen interactions based on molecular structure.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "15-10": (
    caption: [The fixation of complement proteins (补体蛋白固定). The formation of an antibody-antigen complex causes complement protein C4 to be split into two subunits—C4a and C4b. The C4b subunit attaches (is fixed) to the membrane of the cell to be destroyed (such as a bacterium). This event triggers the activation of other complement proteins, some of which attach to the C4b on the membrane surface, initiating a cascade reaction (级联反应).],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "15-11": (
    caption: [The membrane attack complex (膜攻击复合物, MAC). Fixed complement proteins C5 through C9 assemble in the plasma membrane of the victim cell as a membrane attack complex. This complex forms a large pore that punctures the membrane and thereby promotes the destruction of the cell through osmotic lysis (渗透性裂解).],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "15-12": (
    caption: [The effect of an antigen on B and T lymphocytes. A given antigen can stimulate the production of both B lymphocyte clones (B淋巴细胞克隆) and T lymphocyte clones (T淋巴细胞克隆). The ability to produce B lymphocyte clones is influenced by the relative effects of helper T lymphocytes (辅助性T淋巴细胞) and suppressor T lymphocytes (抑制性T淋巴细胞), demonstrating the complex interactions in adaptive immunity (适应性免疫).],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "15-13": (
    caption: [Migration of antigen-presenting dendritic cells (抗原呈递树突状细胞) to secondary lymphoid organs (次级淋巴器官) activates T cells. Once the T cells have been activated by antigens presented to them by the dendritic cells, the activated cells divide to produce a clone. Some of these cells then migrate from the lymphoid organ into the blood. Once in the blood, these activated T cells can home in on the site of the infection because of chemoattractant molecules (化学引诱分子) produced during inflammation.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "15-14": (
    caption: [Coreceptors (共受体) on helper and killer T cells. A foreign antigen is presented to T lymphocytes in association with MHC molecules (主要组织相容性复合体分子). The CD4 on helper T cells, and CD8 coreceptors on killer T cells, permit each type of T cell to interact only with a specific class of MHC molecule—CD4+ helper T cells recognize class-2 MHC (MHC-II类), while CD8+ killer T cells recognize class-1 MHC (MHC-I类).],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "15-15": (
    caption: [Interactions between antigen-presenting cells, T cells, and B cells. An antigen-presenting cell, which here is a macrophage, presents a foreign antigen bound to a class-2 MHC molecule on its surface to a helper T cell. The T cell receptor (T细胞受体, TCR) requires that the antigen be presented in this way in order for the T cell to become activated, demonstrating the requirement for dual recognition in T cell activation.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "15-16": (
    caption: [A killer T cell (杀伤性T细胞) destroys an infected cell. In order for a killer T cell to destroy a cell infected with viruses, the T cell must interact with both the foreign antigen and the class-1 MHC molecule on the surface of the infected cell. This dual recognition ensures that killer T cells only destroy cells that are truly infected and belong to the body.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "15-17": (
    caption: [Interactions between macrophages, helper T cells, and killer T cells. An antigen-presenting cell (macrophage) activates a helper T cell by presenting it with a viral antigen in association with a class-2 MHC molecule. The helper T cell secretes interleukin-2 (白细胞介素-2, IL-2), which promotes the proliferation (增殖) of activated killer T cells. The killer T cells then destroy the cells infected with the viruses.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "15-18": (
    caption: [Interactions between macrophages, helper T cells, and B cells. An antigen-presenting cell (macrophage) activates a helper T cell by presenting it with a foreign antigen in association with a class-2 MHC molecule. The activated helper T cell then interacts with a B cell specific for that antigen. This stimulates the B cell to divide and form a clone, some members of which become plasma cells that secrete antibodies, illustrating the cooperation required between cell types in humoral immunity (体液免疫).],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "15-19": (
    caption: [Virulence (毒力) and antigenicity (抗原性). Active immunity (主动免疫) to a pathogen can be gained by exposure to the fully virulent form or by inoculation with a pathogen whose virulence has been attenuated (减弱) without altering its antigenicity. Upon subsequent exposure to the same pathogen, active immunity protects against infection. This is the basis for vaccination (疫苗接种).],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "15-20": (
    caption: [The primary and secondary immune responses (初次和再次免疫应答). A comparison of antibody production in the primary response (upon first exposure to an antigen) to antibody production in the secondary response (upon subsequent exposure to the antigen). The more rapid and greater production of antibodies in the secondary response is believed to be due to the development of memory cells during the primary response, resulting in faster and stronger protection.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "15-21": (
    caption: [The clonal selection theory (克隆选择学说) as applied to B lymphocytes. Most members of the B lymphocyte clone become memory cells, but some become antibody-secreting plasma cells. This theory explains how the immune system can produce specific antibodies against virtually any antigen through the selection and proliferation of pre-existing lymphocyte clones.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "15-22": (
    caption: [T cell destruction of a cancer cell. A killer T cell contacts a cancer cell (the larger cell), in a manner that requires specific interaction with antigens on the cancer cell surface. The killer T cell releases lymphokines (淋巴因子), including toxins such as perforin (穿孔素) that cause the death of the cancer cell, demonstrating the role of cellular immunity in immunological surveillance (免疫监视) against cancer.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "15-23": (
    caption: [The mechanism of immediate hypersensitivity (速发型超敏反应). Allergy (变态反应) is produced when antibodies of the IgE subclass attach to tissue mast cells. The combination of these antibodies with allergens (变应原, antigens that provoke an allergic reaction) causes the mast cells to secrete histamine and other mediators of inflammation, resulting in symptoms such as itching, swelling, and increased mucus secretion.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "15-24": (
    caption: [A skin test for allergy (皮肤过敏试验). If an allergen is injected into the skin of a sensitive individual, a typical flare-and-wheal response (红斑和风团反应) occurs within several minutes, demonstrating immediate hypersensitivity. This test is used to identify specific allergens to which a person is sensitive.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "15-25": (
    caption: [Common allergens (常见变应原). (a) A scanning electron micrograph of ragweed (豚草) pollen (Ambrosia), which is responsible for hay fever (花粉热). (b) A scanning electron micrograph of house dust mites (屋尘螨) (Dermatophagoides farinae). Waste-product particles produced by the dust mite are often responsible for chronic allergic rhinitis (变应性鼻炎) and asthma (哮喘).],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "table-15-1": (
    caption: [Structures and defense mechanisms of nonspecific (innate) immunity (非特异性免疫/固有免疫). This table summarizes the physical and chemical barriers that provide the first line of defense against pathogens, including skin, digestive tract secretions, respiratory tract mucus and cilia, and alveolar macrophages, demonstrating the multiple layers of innate immune protection.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "table-15-2": (
    caption: [Phagocytic cells (吞噬细胞) and their locations. This table lists the major types of phagocytic cells in the body, including neutrophils in blood and tissues, monocytes in blood that differentiate into tissue macrophages, organ-specific phagocytes such as Kupffer cells in the liver, alveolar macrophages in the lungs, and microglia in the central nervous system, illustrating the widespread distribution of phagocytic cells throughout the body.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "table-15-3": (
    caption: [Effects of interferons (干扰素). This table summarizes the multiple effects of interferons, including inhibition of viral replication (病毒复制), stimulation of macrophage activity, enhancement of natural killer cell activity, and modulation of the adaptive immune response, demonstrating their role as important cytokines in antiviral defense.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "table-15-4": (
    caption: [Comparison of B and T lymphocytes (B淋巴细胞和T淋巴细胞的比较). This table contrasts the characteristics, development, functions, and roles of B and T lymphocytes in the adaptive immune system. B cells are responsible for humoral immunity through antibody production, while T cells mediate cellular immunity and regulate immune responses.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "table-15-5": (
    caption: [Summary of events in a local inflammation (局部炎症的事件总结). This table outlines the sequence of events during inflammation, including vasodilation, increased vascular permeability, recruitment of phagocytes, release of chemical mediators such as histamine and prostaglandins, and the resolution phase, providing a comprehensive overview of the inflammatory response.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "table-15-6": (
    caption: [The immunoglobulins (免疫球蛋白). This table describes the five classes of antibodies (IgG, IgM, IgA, IgD, IgE) and their functions. IgG provides long-term immunity, IgM is the first antibody produced in response to infection, IgA protects mucosal surfaces, IgD serves as a B cell receptor, and IgE mediates allergic reactions, showing the diversity of antibody functions.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "table-15-7": (
    caption: [Some cytokines (细胞因子) that regulate the immune system. This table lists important cytokines including interleukins (白细胞介素), interferons, tumor necrosis factor (肿瘤坏死因子), and their biological functions in regulating immune cell proliferation, differentiation, and activation, demonstrating the complex network of chemical signals that coordinate immune responses.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "table-15-8": (
    caption: [Summary of the clonal selection theory (克隆选择学说总结) as applied to B cells. This table outlines the process by which B cells are selected and activated by specific antigens, leading to clonal expansion and differentiation into plasma cells and memory cells, explaining how the immune system achieves specificity and immunological memory.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "table-15-9": (
    caption: [Comparison of active and passive immunity (主动免疫和被动免疫的比较). This table contrasts active immunity (acquired through infection or vaccination) with passive immunity (acquired through transfer of antibodies), including their onset time, duration, and sources, helping to understand different approaches to achieving immune protection.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "table-15-10": (
    caption: [Some examples of autoimmune diseases (自身免疫性疾病的例子). This table lists various autoimmune diseases such as Hashimoto's disease (桥本氏病), Graves' disease (格雷夫斯病), rheumatoid arthritis (类风湿性关节炎), systemic lupus erythematosus (系统性红斑狼疮), and myasthenia gravis (重症肌无力), along with their affected organs and mechanisms, illustrating how immune system dysfunction can lead to disease.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "table-15-11": (
    caption: [Allergy: Comparison of immediate and delayed hypersensitivity reactions (速发型和迟发型超敏反应的比较). This table contrasts immediate hypersensitivity (mediated by IgE antibodies and mast cells, occurring within minutes) with delayed hypersensitivity (mediated by T cells, occurring within 1-3 days), including their mechanisms, mediators, and examples such as anaphylaxis (过敏性休克) and contact dermatitis (接触性皮炎).],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  )
)
